---
/** Personal finance: lifetime IRS tax paid. */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import LifetimeTaxCalculator from '../../components/calculators/LifetimeTaxCalculator.tsx';
import { lifetimeTax } from '../../lib/personal-finance';
import { formatMoney, formatPct } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = lifetimeTax({ currentAge: 40, careerStartAge: 22, retireAge: 65, currentIncome: 75000, incomeGrowth: 0.03, contribution401kPct: 0.06, status: 'single', stateCode: 'CA' });
const tx = lifetimeTax({ currentAge: 40, careerStartAge: 22, retireAge: 65, currentIncome: 75000, incomeGrowth: 0.03, contribution401kPct: 0.06, status: 'single', stateCode: 'TX' });
---

<Base
  title="Lifetime tax calculator 2026 — what you pay over a career"
  description="A running total of federal, state and FICA tax on your labor income across a whole career — and how much a no-income-tax state or a 401(k) changes it."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">Personal finance · tax</p>
    <h1>Lifetime tax paid</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Tax is paid in slices you barely notice. Added up across a whole career, the total is a number worth seeing — here it is.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Each paycheck's tax feels small, and that's the point — it's withheld before you see it. Summed across a
    40-plus-year career, federal income tax, state income tax and FICA add up to one of the largest expenses of your
    life. This projects that lifetime total from your income and career span, using the same verified 2026 rates as
    the rest of the site.
  </p>

  <LifetimeTaxCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>A {formatMoney(75000)} earner in California, age 22 to 65, 3% raises, contributing 6% to a 401(k):</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Line</th><th>Over the career</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Total career income</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalIncome)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Federal income tax</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalFederal)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>California income tax</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalState)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Your FICA</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalEmployeeFICA)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Total you personally pay</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalPersonalPaid)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Effective lifetime rate</td><td>{formatPct(ex.effectiveLifetimeRate)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    That's {formatMoney(ex.totalPersonalPaid)} in tax over a career — {formatPct(ex.effectiveLifetimeRate)} of
    lifetime income, before counting the {formatMoney(ex.totalEmployerFICA)} of employer FICA the government also
    collects on your labor. The same career in Texas, with no state income tax, pays
    {' '}{formatMoney(ex.totalPersonalPaid - tx.totalPersonalPaid)} less — that's the lifetime value of the state line.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does this include employer FICA?</h3>
    <p>It shows both: what you personally pay from your paychecks, and the total the government collects including
      your employer's matching FICA. Employer FICA is a tax on your labor you never see on a pay stub, but it's part
      of the cost of employing you.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does it include sales, property or gas tax?</h3>
    <p>No — only taxes on labor income: federal, state and FICA. Add consumption and property taxes and the true
      lifetime total would be materially higher.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How do I lower the number?</h3>
    <p>Three big levers: pre-tax contributions (401(k), HSA, traditional IRA) that cut taxable income now; living in
      a no-income-tax state, which zeroes the state line; and, for the self-employed, entity choices like an S-corp
      election. The calculator lets you test the first two directly.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/paycheck-calculator/">Paycheck calculator</a> — one year's version of this</li>
    <li><a href="/self-employed-retirement-calculator/">Self-employed retirement</a> — shelter more, pre-tax</li>
    <li><a href="/fire-calculator/">FIRE calculator</a> — the wealth side of the same career</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">A projection from today's income across a whole career, on 2026 rates — an estimate, not a record. Not tax or financial advice.</p>
</Base>
